         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Dunrobin ¶ 12.6.76. ¶  ¶ Am I correct my dear Baron in naming the enclosed plant No. 36 of my collection Solanum adenophorum. F.v.M. Frag. II 162? ¶  ¶ The description as far as I can make it out tall...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">76.06.12</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From William Armit</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M109, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Dunrobin<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Qld.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">12.6.76.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Am I correct my dear Baron in naming the enclosed plant No. 36 of my collection <name key="Solanum%20adenophorum">Solanum adenophorum</name>. F.v.M. Frag. II 162?<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B61.05.02, p. 162.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The description as far as I can make it out tallies with that in Flora Aust. I. 460.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Solanum%20adenophorum">Solanum adenophorum</name>
                     </seg> is described in Bentham (1863-78), vol. 4, p. 460.</p>
               </note> The locality is at Head of Etheridge River on Newcastle Range.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Qld.</p>
               </note> No. 236 which I sent you tallies I think with S. petrophilum F.v.M. in Linnea XXV. 433.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B53.04.01, p. 433.</p>
               </note> The Calyx is prominently ribbed &amp; is almost reduced to the five linear ribs in the fruit. This species also often has white flowers at least I judge it to be the same from its general appearance. Common here on the Etheridge.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Etheridge River, Qld.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I could not find any fruiting specimens of No. 36 or would have gathered them. I am getting a better sort of Field Book made 19 x 12 with boards as described in Balfours "Botanists Companion.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Balfour (1860).</p>
               </note> I find that the leather one which I carry bulges when many papers are put into it. It is common harness leather for I could not get sole leather up here. I intend to have two. As I generally have plenty of Packhorses &amp; when out for a month I often am sorely puzzled how to carry all my specimens.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have a dry cone of C. Cairnsiana<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Cycas%20cairnsiana">Cycas cairnsiana</name>
                     </seg>.</p>
               </note> which I brought with me from the Robinson<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Robinson River, NT? No other evidence has been found that Armit was as far west as this at this period.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> I mean the young fruiting branches which form in a knob on the summit of the stem. Would you like to have it? I also enclose a small plant which I found on the Gilbert River.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Qld.</p>
               </note> Flower white leaves 2 close to the ground flower on long style.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Yours truly</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>William. E. Armit</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
